    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1952-12-31T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1946-11-04T00:00:00-05:00" n="350" subtype="editorial-note"
                type="document" xml:id="d350">
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Editorial Note</hi>
                </head>
                <p>There follows a list of certain Department of State position papers or
                    “Instructions” which were prepared for the guidance of the United States
                    Delegation to the Sixth Regular Session of the General Assembly which was to
                    convene at Paris on November 6, 1951. These papers were organized into a
                    Delegation book entitled <hi rend="italic">Soviet Peace Propaganda at the 6th
                            <gloss target="#t_GA1">GA</gloss>.</hi>
                    <list>
                        <label>1.</label>
                        <item>“Present status of problem of provision of armed forces for use by
                            Security Council pursuant to Article 43” (Doc. <gloss target="#t_SD1"
                                >SD</gloss>/A/243, September 27, 1951);</item>
                        <label>2.</label>
                        <item>“Possible Soviet charges of discriminatory United States trade
                            policies” (Doc. <gloss target="#t_SD1">SD</gloss>/A/244, October 6,
                            1951);</item>
                        <label>3.</label>
                        <item>“World Peace Council” (Doc. <gloss target="#t_SD1">SD</gloss>/A/245,
                            September 11, 1951);</item>
                        <label>4.</label>
                        <item>“Five Power Pact proposal of the Soviet Union” (Doc. <gloss
                                target="#t_SD1">SD</gloss>/A/246, October 9, 1951);</item>
                        <label>5.</label>
                        <item>“United States position on Resolution 377 (V) C (Syrian-Iraq
                            resolution calling for Big Five meetings and report thereon)” (Doc.
                                <gloss target="#t_SD1">SD</gloss>/A/247, October 1, 1947);</item>
                        <label>6.</label>
                        <item>“General Assembly resolution on regional and collective self-defense
                            organizations” (Doc. <gloss target="#t_SD1">SD</gloss>/A/249, October
                            10, 1951);</item>
                        <pb facs="0499" n="477" xml:id="pg_477"/>
                        <label>7.</label>
                        <item>“Soviet propaganda tactics in the General Assembly” (Doc. <gloss
                                target="#t_SD1">SD</gloss>/A/250, October 10, 1951);</item>
                        <label>8.</label>
                        <item>“Soviet charges on establishment of United States military bases”
                            (Doc. <gloss target="#t_SD1">SD</gloss>/A/252, October 19, 1951);</item>
                        <label>9.</label>
                        <item>“Possible Soviet proposals for information-cultural exchanges” (Doc.
                                <gloss target="#t_SD1">SD</gloss>/A/253, October 19, 1951).</item>
                    </list>
                </p>
